    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-05-26T06:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-05-26T06:30:00-05:00" n="245"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d245">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">845.00/1961: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Officer in Charge at New Delhi</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merrell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-05-26T18:00:00+06:30"
                            >May 26, 1943—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>365. The following communiqué was issued this afternoon by the Government: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The Government of India have received request from Mr. Gandhi to forward
                            a short letter from himself to Mr. Jinnah expressing a wish to meet him.
                            In accordance with their known policy in regard to correspondence or
                            interviews with Mr. Gandhi, the Government of India has decided the
                            letter could not be forwarded and have so informed Mr. Gandhi and Mr.
                            Jinnah. They are not prepared to establish facilities for political
                            correspondence or contact to a person detained for promoting an illegal
                            mass movement which is not disavowed and thus gravely embarrassing
                            India’s war effort at a critical time. It rests with Mr. Gandhi to
                            satisfy the Government of India that he can safely be allowed once more
                            to participate in the public affairs of this country and until he does
                            so the disabilities from which he suffers are of his own choice.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0235" n="223" xml:id="pg_223"/>
                <p>In his speech at the annual meeting of the Muslim League in April Jinnah said
                    [“]Nobody would welcome it more than myself if Mr. Gandhi is even now really
                    willing to come to a settlement with the Muslims on the basis of Pakistan.…<note
                        n="48" xml:id="d245fn48">Omission indicated in the original telegram.</note>
                    If he has made up his mind what is there to prevent Mr. Gandhi from writing
                    direct to me”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Merrell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
